pullRequest.body:
We provide macros for the following notations:
- `‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô` denotes the `m`-dimensional simplex in the `n`-truncated simplex category.
- `X _‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô` denotes the `m`-th term of an `n`-truncated simplicial object `X`.
- `X ^‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô` denotes the `m`-th term of an `n`-truncated cosimplicial object `X`.

For all of these notations, the truncation proof `p : m ‚â§ n` can also be provided using the syntax `‚¶ãm, p‚¶å‚Çô`, `X _‚¶ãm, p‚¶å‚Çô`, and `X ^‚¶ãm, p‚¶å‚Çô`, respectively.

These notations generalize those already in use in `HomotopyCat.lean` and `Coskeletal.lean`.

Delaborators for these notations are added in #20719.

See #17732 and #20355 to understand the reason for the use of `subscriptTerm`.

This seems good to me, but some expert in meta code should also have a look.
LGTM modulo Mario's comment
The meta code looks fine to me.
LGTM modulo Mario's comment

This change would also allow removing many of the `([n] : SimplexCategory)` type annotations in this file and elsewhere (though maybe this suggests there is a reason it hasn't been done before).

I can open a separate PR removing obsolete type annotations.

I have little understanding of the detailed syntax of notations and of meta code, but `[...]` may conflict with list notations. However, as a scoped `Simplicial` notation, we can certainly increase the priority.

Unfortunately `scoped[Simplicial] syntax` is not possible (unless #18230 is merged), so currently `open SimplexCategory.Truncated` brings the `[m]‚Çô` notation into scope. Do you think this notation also being given `(priority := high)` could cause any problems?
hopefully #18230 is compiling soon, I've adopted that PR now :)

#21565 changed the notation for objects of the simplex category, and I have done the same for the truncated simplex category notation in this PR. The new syntax allows removing `(priority := high)`.

I still think it would be a good idea to make this notation `scoped[Simplicial]` after #18230 lands.
How expensive is `omega`? Is this the right balance of things to try before delegating to `omega`?
I remain opposed to introducing any notations that conflict with `List` notation. This is not on any technical grounds, but simply that they *reduce readability* relative to no notation.

@kim-em to be sure I understand, could you please clarify which of the following you are suggesting?
- Remove the existing notation `[n]` completely.
- Remove the `(priority := high)` added to the `[n]` notation declaration in this PR.
- Change the proposed notation `[m]‚Çô`, added in this PR.
- Get rid of both notations `[n]` and `[m]‚Çô`.
I would suggest changing the existing notation `[_]` (as it is barely usable because of the conflict with the list notation) and change `[_]‚Çô` accordingly.

(Not fully serious suggestions). There is `\[--]` in the [abbreviations list](https://github.com/leanprover/vscode-lean/blob/master/src/abbreviation/abbreviations.json) already (and used in mathlib for unrelated concepts): `‚ÅÖm‚ÅÜ`, `‚ÅÖm‚ÅÜ‚Çô`. But otherwise, the selection of unicode characters which resemble brackets is not that extensive, some examples are: `‚¶óm‚¶ò‚Çô`, `‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô`.

On a more serious note, whatever the notation will be, we can (and probably should) PR a `\simplex` command to the list yielding this notation.
It could be a good idea to seek advice/suggestions about alternative notations on Zulip?
Agreed. Thanks all for the suggestions. I will get a Zulip thread going and see if others are willing to weigh in.
The notation for objects of the simplex category has been changed in #21565. I will update this PR to reflect the same change for objects of the truncated simplex category.
This should be `scoped` or even `local`, since `trunc` is too common a name to be reserved globally for simplex categories

```suggestion
  "‚¶ã" term "‚¶å" noWs subscriptTerm (noWs "'" term)? : term
```
This mirrors the notation of getElem optional proofs.

I like the potential for mirroring `getElem` here, but I wasn't able to get this exact syntax working. From [these](https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/blob/4877e8403133097a5c199a8d84ad52d0fcd1c200/tests/lean/run/atomValidation.lean#L49-L63) tests, it seems this is an intentional restriction.

Alternatives could include using a double single quote, `"''"`, using a similar unicode character (see [here](https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/blob/4877e8403133097a5c199a8d84ad52d0fcd1c200/tests/lean/run/atomValidation.lean#L116-L120)), or moving the single quote to the other side of the subscript, `"‚¶å'"`.

I am not sure what the best next step is here. I am happy to change the syntax, but I haven't figured out a way to get the suggested syntax working and none of the alternatives jump out at me as an obvious fit.

Any suggestions, @digama0 @joelriou?

I think the best option would be to just avoid using this form altogether and ensure the proof is always implicit. But if we need a syntax for technical reasons, I guess we can just keep it as is. (Other alternatives include more heavyweight syntax like `[n]‚ÇÇ (h := by decide)`.)

To be honest, I'm not sure if the ability to provide an explicit proof is needed or not. It's very nice to have for experimenting, but one can always fall back to the more explicit constructor.

My (loosely held) opinion is that it may be best to leave as-is for now, then we can always improve the syntax for explicit proofs if it turns up frequently in polished code.

However, I am also happy to remove the syntax for explicit proofs or implement an alternative syntax like `[n]‚ÇÇ (h := by decide)`.
